quote<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :O --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/embarassed.gif ALT=":O"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  riginally posted by JanneM:<br>
The server won't need all that much of a CPU; far more important is plenty of memory or a speedy disk subsystem.<br>
/Janne<br>
<br>
Actually, the server is farily CPU heavy. In terms of CPU time, the client is very light. Since the server runs all the game AI (including pathfinding) it is currently fairly demanding. We still have a lot of optomization to do, but the server will always be quite CPU hungry. You are quite correct about the memory though. more ram==good. The fast disk will cut loading times and is more important for the client as graphics are much heavier in file size than game data<br>
--------------------<br>
Trent Oster<br>
Producer - NWN<br>
Bioware Corp. <br>
<br>
NWN Story <br>
The story in NWN has just undergone a series of revisions. Our Director of Design at Bioware, James Ohlen (lead designer BG, Co-lead BGII) has assisted us with our recent revisions and they story is shaping up very strong. In a number of ways the NWN storyline will be even more compelling than the BGII storyline. We can't take a step back in quality in any aspect of NWN. We shipped BGII with a great story and our fans responded, so NWN will feature the same attention to story and adventure, with the added benefit of the lessons learned from BG and BGII. In short, The NWN story is going to be the best story we can create, single player or multiplayer. It's your choice.<br>
--------------------<br>
<br>
Trent Oster<br>
Producer - NWN<br>
Bioware Corp. <br>
<br>
Time Stop <br>
Time Stop. <br>
If a mage gets Time Stop off the combat is over. Bloody nasty spell. We are looking at the protection / breaching balancing in the spells and we may have to get a little creative here and there. In the end we will make the game the best balanced D&amp;D game we can. <br>
-------------------- <br>
Trent Oster <br>
Producer - NWN <br>
Bioware Corp. <br>
